        <name xml:lang="en">urea</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Calculated value based on stoichiometric calculations and literature data. 
60.05564g/mol is the molar mass of urea, as N (CH4N2O). 
97.09476g/mol is the molar mass of sulfamic acid (H3NSO3). 

Sulfamic acid is produced by the reaction of urea, sulfur trioxide and sulfuric acid. No other production routes are currently used. The process can be described in two steps. First urea is mixed with sulfuric acid and sulfur trioxide. This step requires a temperature below 40 degrees Celsius, to avoid carbon dioxide formation. Secondly the product of the first step reacts with the remaining sulfur trioxide. This step requires temperatures of 50 to 80 degrees and entails the formation of carbon dioxide together with sulfamic acid (Metzger 2000).
Chemical reaction:
NH2CONH2 + SO3 + H2SO4 -&gt; 2NH2SO3H + CO2</comment>
